%I A164322 #13 Jun 15 2026 00:44:05
%S A164322 14,67673,25688777
%N A164322 Numbers m such that m = prime(P) + sigma(P), where P is product of digits of m.
%C A164322 The product of the digits of next term (if it exists) is greater than 2*10^8.
%C A164322 The sequence is finite with all terms < 10^70. Indeed, since P is a product of primes 2, 3, 5, 7, we have sigma(P) < (2/1)*(3/2)*(5/4)*(7/6)*P = (35/8)*P. For an L-digit m, we have P <= 9^L, and using Dusart's upper bound for prime(9^L), we get prime(P) + sigma(P) < prime(9^L) + (35/8)*9^L < 10^(L-1) <= m whenever L > 70. - _Max Alekseyev_, Jun 12 2026
%C A164322 No other terms below 10^16. The sequence is likely complete. - _Max Alekseyev_, Jun 13 2026
%e A164322 25688777 = prime(2*5*6*8*8*7*7*7) + sigma(2*5*6*8*8*7*7*7), so 25688777 is in the sequence.
%t A164322 Do[If[n=Prime[m]+DivisorSigma[1,m];m==Apply[Times,IntegerDigits[n]],Print[n]], {m,200000000}]
%Y A164322 Cf. A000040, A000203, A164323, A164324.
%K A164322 base,bref,fini,more,nonn
%O A164322 1,1
%A A164322 _Farideh Firoozbakht_, Aug 13 2009
